<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-475-784  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 475 784.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  July 27 1989 n1174 p14(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>One small step for computers. (the co-evolution of computer andspace technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hunter, Philip.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Space technology, particularly NASA's Apollo project, had greatinfluence on computer technology during its infancy.andP;  Computerswere and still are used in every facet of space exploration, fromdesigning a spacecraft to controlling flight and capturing andanalyzing scientific data.andP;  Progress in space computers has slowedas much as the rest of the space program.andP;  NASA uses computersthat are decades out of date even in the sophisticated spaceshuttle.andP;  Using older computers is expensive because of the numberof support personnel needed.andP;  As planning for the space stationproceeds, more current computer technologies are being called intouse.andP;  Expert systems and improved CAD-CAM applications are used inmission planning and spacecraft design while high-level languageshave improved software quality and maintainability.andP;  The spacestation project may result in more advances in computertechnology.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     History of ComputingSpace ExplorationHistoryHigh TechnologyFuture TechnologiesUnited States. National Aeronautics and Space Administration.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>